A reward function should satisfy no-op invariance: if a designated no-op action leaves the environment state unchanged, then taking that action must yield no additional reward beyond the do-nothing baseline. Formally, for any state s and no-op a₀ such that T(s,a₀)=s, one requires R(s,a₀,s)=0, or more generally equal to the baseline reward for inaction. Over repeated no-ops, the cumulative discounted return must therefore not increase: if s_{t+1}=s_t under a₀, then E[∑_{t=0}^{n-1} γ^t R(s_t,a₀,s_t)] should remain at baseline rather than grow. This prevents the agent from gaining reward without causing any task-relevant change. A stronger equivalent view is state-change consistency: reward should depend on the realized change in world state, not on an action label that does nothing. So a no-op must never be a source of strictly positive exploitable reward.
